  { question: "What is Base64 encoding?", answer: "Base64 is a binary-to-text encoding scheme that represents binary data using 64 ASCII characters (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, +, /). It is commonly used to embed binary data in text-based formats like JSON, XML, HTML, and email." },
  { question: "Why does Base64 increase the data size?", answer: "Base64 uses 4 characters to represent every 3 bytes of input data, resulting in approximately 33% size increase. This trade-off is accepted because the encoded text is safe to transmit through text-only channels that might corrupt raw binary data." },
  { question: "What is URL-safe Base64?", answer: "URL-safe Base64 replaces the + and / characters with - and _ respectively, making the encoded string safe to use in URLs and filenames without additional percent-encoding. The padding character = may also be omitted." },
